\subsection{The Single-user Scenario}
Figure \ref{fig:fig_2} and Figure \ref{fig:fig_3} display the GMI of the mixed-ADC architecture under rectangular or exponential power delay profile, respectively. Several observations can be made from both figures. First, we notice that the GMI lower and upper bounds are very tight, and thus we are allowed to only use the GMI lower bound in the subsequent spectral efficiency evaluation. In addition, for the special case of $K=N$, there is a barely visible gap between $I_{\mathrm{GMI}}^{\mathrm{lower}}$ and the capacity of the ideal conventional architecture, as predicted by Corollary \ref{cor:cor_1}. Moreover, the mixed-ADC architecture with a small proportion of high-resolution ADCs does achieve a dominant portion of the capacity of ideal conventional architecture, and significantly outperform antenna selection with the same number of high-resolution ADCs.

Further, Figure \ref{fig:fig_4} gives a comparison of the GMI lower bounds under two different power delay profiles. In general, the gap is marginal for various $K$ and $\mathrm{SNR}$ in consideration. Therefore in the following we may confine ourselves to the rectangular power delay profile. Besides, we notice that for each given SNR, there is an intersection between the curves. This will be explained detailedly in the following.

The impact of $T$ on $I_{\mathrm{GMI}}^{\mathrm{lower}}$ is addressed by Figure \ref{fig:fig_5}, where three different choices of $T$ are made. For each given SNR, we notice that there is also an intersection between two of the curves. Particularly, if $K$ lays at the left side of the intersection, a larger $T$ would achieve a higher $I_{\mathrm{GMI}}^{\mathrm{lower}}$. Because in this situation, there are few high-resolution ADCs and, hence, frequency diversity becomes crucial for signal recovery at the receiver. If $K$ lays at the right side of the intersection, on the other hand, a larger $T$ would lead to a lower $I_{\mathrm{GMI}}^{\mathrm{lower}}$, and this may be attributed to the limitation of the linear frequency-domain equalizer in mitigating ICI.

Figure \ref{fig:fig_6} further investigates the impact of SNR on $I_{\mathrm{GMI}}^{\mathrm{lower}}$, focusing on little $K$ particularly. Red dashed line corresponds to the limit of $I_{\mathrm{GMI}}^{\mathrm{lower}}$ in the high SNR regime. We observe a similar phenomenon\footnote{For one-bit massive SIMO, the GMI (or achievable data rate) increases first and then turns down as the SNR grows large, since the amplitude of the transmit signal can barely be recovered at the receiver when the SNR is sufficient large. For more details, please refer to \cite{jacobsson2015one} and \cite{liang2015mixed}.} as that in frequency-flat SIMO channel scenario \cite[Fig. 6]{liang2015mixed}, except that when $K=0$, the degradation of $I_{\mathrm{GMI}}^{\mathrm{lower}}$ in the high SNR regime tends to level off now. This again may be attributed to the frequency diversity for signal recovery when the SNR is high but there are only one-bit ADCs available.
\subsection{The Multi-user Scenario}
Here we assume rectangular power delay profile, and therefore each tap of the multipath channel from user $v$ to an arbitrary BS antenna is independently $\mathcal{CN}(0,1/T^v)$ distributed.

Figure \ref{fig:fig_7} shows the numerical result for norm-based ADC switch scheme. Several observations are in order. First, we notice that the GMI lower and upper bounds again virtually coincide with each other. Second, due to not applying successive interference cancellation (SIC) at the receiver, there is a visible but marginal performance lose at $K=N$ when compared with the per-user capacity\footnote{The per-user capacity is obtained through dividing the users' sum-capacity by the number of users.} of ideal conventional architecture. Finally, the mixed-ADC architecture with a small proportion of high-resolution ADCs still achieves a large portion of the per-user capacity of ideal conventional architecture, while overwhelms antenna selection with the same number of high-resolution ADCs.

Furthermore, Figure \ref{fig:fig_8} gives a comparison between the random and norm-based ADC switch schemes, choosing $\mathrm{SNR}=-10\mathrm{dB}$ as an example. It implies that the norm-based scheme does achieve slightly better performance than the random switch scheme.
\subsection{BER Performance}
Finally, we examine the BER performance of the mixed-ADC architecture when employing a (2,1,3) convolutional coder and Viterbi hard-decision decoding. We adopt QPSK modulation to map the coded bits into system input $\tilde{\mathbf{x}}$.\footnote{Noting that the optimal linear frequency-domain equalizer in Proposition \ref{prop:prop_1} is dedicated to Gaussian distributed channel inputs, it is mismatched with QPSK modulation and is therefore suboptimal in this situation. Nevertheless, benefiting from the central-limit theorem, the actual channel inputs, $\mathbf{F}^{\dag}\tilde{\mathbf{x}}$, asymptotically approach Gaussian distribution as $Q$ grows large. As a result, the performance loss due to the mismatch is supposed to be marginal.} In this manner, one information bit is first encoded into a couple of codeword bits and then mapped into a QPSK symbol. As a result, $E_{\mathrm{b}}/N_0$ under this setup coincides with $\mathrm{SNR}$.

Numerical results for single-user and multi-user scenarios are given by Figure \ref{fig:fig_9} and Figure \ref{fig:fig_10}, respectively. We notice that with a small proportion of high-resolution ADCs, the mixed-ADC architecture achieves remarkable gain over one-bit massive MIMO. Moreover, in the multi-user scenario, the mixed-ADC architecture with $K=16$ is able to eliminate the error floor encountered by one-bit massive MIMO. These observations again validate the superiority of the mixed-ADC architecture over the uniform-ADC architecture.

\section{Conclusion}
\label{sect:conclusion}
In this paper, we leverage the information-theoretical tool of GMI to analyze the performance of the mixed-ADC architecture under frequency-selective fading. Extensive numerical studies demonstrate that the mixed-ADC architecture with a relatively small number of high-resolution ADCs suffices to achieve data rate close to that of ideal conventional architecture, in both single-user scenario and multi-user scenario. Besides, the mixed-ADC architecture in the multi-user scenario is effective in mitigating the error floor encountered by one-bit massive MIMO. Thus we envision the mixed-ADC architecture as a promising option for effective design of massive MIMO receivers.

Beyond the scope of this paper, several important problems remain unsolved. First, channel estimation and time-frequency synchronization in the mixed-ADC architecture are more challenging than those in ideal conventional architecture, especially in the multi-user scenario, and thus efficient channel estimation and time-frequency synchronization algorithms are urgent for the mixed-ADC architecture to realize the promised profits. In addition, joint channel estimation and time-frequency synchronization is also an interesting and important topic for future research.


